# Cache-Oblivious Algorithms

A cache-oblivious algorithm is designed to minimize cache misses without knowing the cache parameters.

## The Cache Hierarchy

```
CPU  →  L1 (32KB)  →  L2 (256KB)  →  L3 (8MB)  →  RAM  →  Disk
       ~1ns           ~5ns           ~15ns        ~100ns    ~10ms
```

The gap between CPU speed and memory latency is the **memory wall**.

## The Key Idea

Optimize for **cache line usage** (typically 64 bytes). When memory is accessed, an entire cache line is fetched. The goal is to use every byte before the line is evicted.

## Matrix Multiplication: Before & After

**Naïve approach** (cache-unfriendly):

```c
for (i = 0; i < N; i++)
    for (j = 0; j < N; j++)
        for (k = 0; k < N; k++)
            C[i][j] += A[i][k] * B[k][j];  // B accessed column-wise → cache misses!
```

**Cache-oblivious** (recursive blocking):

```c
void multiply(int N, int A[N][N], int B[N][N], int C[N][N]) {
    if (N <= 32) {  // base case fits in cache
        for (i = 0; i < N; i++)
            for (j = 0; j < N; j++)
                for (k = 0; k < N; k++)
                    C[i][j] += A[i][k] * B[k][j];
        return;
    }
    int half = N / 2;
    // Recurse on 8 sub-blocks
    multiply(half, A[0][0], B[0][0], C[0][0]);
    multiply(half, A[0][0], B[0][half], C[0][half]);
    // ... (6 more recursive calls)
}
```

:::evaluate{criteria="cache-analysis"}
### System Critique Challenge
Analyze the cache behavior of both implementations. Why does the recursive version get better cache utilization regardless of cache size?

```c
// Naïve: C[i][j] += A[i][k] * B[k][j]
// Cache-oblivious: recursive divide-and-conquer on blocks
```
:::

## The Z-Order Curve

For even better locality, use the Morton order (Z-order) to store matrix elements:

- Interleave the bits of the row and column indices
- Nearby elements in 2D space → nearby in memory
- Works recursively at every level of the cache hierarchy
